Overview.Summary: The 2016 Moldovan presidential election took place on November 13, 2016 (1). The runoff was between Igor Dodon (pro-Russian socialist PSRM) and Maia Sandu (pro-EU liberal PAS) (1). Dodon was expected to win (1). The election sparked discussion on whether Moldova should continue its pro-Western stance or pivot back to Russia (6,7,9). In July 2016, the Moldovan Parliament adopted a law to protect victims of violence, including the use of a 10-day emergency restraining order (4). U.S. President Barack Obama warned Russia about interfering in the election (8). Dodon, a former president, was defeated by Sandu in the 2020 election (5).
